Poland to this day. Since the mid-1980s, public discourse has repeatedly focussed on the issue of how to deal with the National Socialists' destruction of the Jews. This has raised accusations that the Polish people bore an element of moral or active guilt during World War Two which, however, conflict with the country's long-established perception of itself as a community of heroes and victims. The author examines the question of how Polish society is handling this contradiction and what effect the discussions have on the opinions formed by the population.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)xInfluence. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)zPoland. 0aNational characteristics, PolishxPublic opinion. 0aPublic opinionzPoland. 4aDiskurs. 4aHolocaust. 4aPolen. 4aShoah. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Eastern.2bisacsh  aDiscourse.  aHolocaust.  aPoland.  aShoah.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA History 2000 - 2014z9783110635836oZDB-23-GHI08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK GESAMTPAKET / COMPLETE PACKAGE 2013z9783110317350oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PAKET GESCHICHTE, POLITIKWISS., SOZIOLOGIE 2013z9783110317114oZDB-23-DPS0 cprintz978311027437040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783110274448zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110274448zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110274448/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DGGb2013  aZDB-23-DPSb2013  aZDB-23-GHIc2000d2014  aZDB-23-GOA